Question 1

Determine if the variable is stationary. Provide any and all evidence you have to support your answer (e.g.plots, ADF test statistic, etc.). 

#plotting series 1
ggplot(data=data) +
  geom_line(aes(x=date, y=series_one), colour="hotpink") +
  ggtitle("Series 1 Levels") +
  labs(y = "Series 1", x = "Date")

Series 1 is not stationary. First, the graph appears to have somewhat of a trend. However, that trend is only in the middle section of the data and the oldest and most recent years appear to be moving toward what might be classified as the mean of the series. Potentially, if we had more years of data, we might see that the series is actually stationary. However, with the amount of data we have here, we see no evidence to suggest it is.

Further, using the Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test, we fail to reject the null that the data is non-stationary at every level from 1% to 10%.

intord(data$series_one)

## $test_results
##   level crit_value ADF_round1_stat ADF_round2_stat round_1_dec round_2_dec
## 1   10%      -2.57           -1.02           -9.39         FTR         REJ
## 2    5%      -2.87           -1.02           -9.39         FTR         REJ
## 3    1%      -3.45           -1.02           -9.39         FTR         REJ

However, Series 1 could be difference stationary. When we plot the first difference, we see a graph that looks mean reverting and homoskedastic. The ADF test also suggests the dats is difference stationary as we can reject the null of non-stationarity at the 1% level and the ACF for the first difference is much faster decaying than the ACF for the levels. The decision heuristic also supports the conclusion of difference stationarity as the standard deviation falls by almost 30 units after differencing.

#take first difference

data <- data %>%
  mutate(first_diff_series_1 = difference(series_one, difference = 1)) %>%
  mutate(sec_diff_series_1 = difference(series_one, difference = 2))

##plot first difference
ggplot(data=data) +
  geom_line(aes(x=date, y=first_diff_series_1), colour="hotpink") +
  ggtitle("1st Differenced Series 1") +
  labs(y = "Series 1", x = "Date")
## Warning: Removed 1 row containing missing values (`geom_line()`).

Plot the ACF and PACF functions and indicate if you think this should be an AR, MA, or ARMA model. From these plots choose a starting set of lags and run the appropriate regression reporting the coefficients and model fit statistics.

The PACF decays much faster than the ACF. This indicates that we should model series one as an AR model. According to the PACF, we should use 3 lags.

#plot acf and pacf
par(mfrow = c(1,2))
acf(data$series_one, lag.max = 24)
pacf(data$series_one, lag.max = 24)

Using the ARIMA function with 3 p lags, we get 3 statistically significant coefficients for our lags as well as a BIC of 1054.58 and an AIC of 1036.27.

#generate first arma model
arma1 <- Arima(data$series_one, order = c(3,0,0))
summary(arma1)

I have decided to use BIC to evaluate the models as I believe picking a parsimonious model means that our chosen specification only uses the explanatory variables that have a large effect on overall fit. Question 2

Using the variable series_two from the data file, complete the following:

Determine if the variable is stationary. Provide any and all evidence you have to support your answer (e.g.plots, ADF test statistic, etc.).

Series two appears to have somewhat of a trend. When we look at the intord function, we find a lot of evidence to suggest the series is difference stationary. A visual inspection, the ADF test, the decision heuristic, and the faster declining differenced ACF as compared to the levels ACF support the conclusion of difference stationarity.

However, the levels graph shows a strong trend, I detrended the data and see that the detrended graph also appears mean reverting and homoskedastic. It is clear that the data is not stationary at the levels but could be either difference or trend stationary.

#plotting series 2
ggplot(data=data) +
  geom_line(aes(x=date, y=series_two), colour="hotpink") +
  ggtitle("Series 2 Levels") +
  labs(y = "Series 2", x = "Date")

intord(data$series_two)

## $test_results
##   level crit_value ADF_round1_stat ADF_round2_stat round_1_dec round_2_dec
## 1   10%      -2.57           -1.41           -9.85         FTR         REJ
## 2    5%      -2.87           -1.41           -9.85         FTR         REJ
## 3    1%      -3.45           -1.41           -9.85         FTR         REJ
#detrend the data
model <- lm(series_two ~ date, data = data)
detrend_series2 <- data %>%
  mutate(detrended_series2 = series_two - predict(model))

#plot detrended data
ggplot(data=detrend_series2) +
  geom_line(aes(x=date, y=detrended_series2), colour="hotpink") +
  ggtitle("Detrended Series 2") +
  labs(y = "Series 2", x = "Date")

Plot the ACF and PACF functions and indicate if you think this should be an AR, MA, or ARMA model. From these plots choose a starting set of lags and run the appropriate regression reporting the coefficients and model fit statistics.

The PACF declines much faster than the ACF, suggesting that this is an AR model. My first model will have 4 AR lags and 1 difference since the previous question indicated that this data is likely difference stationary.

Plot the ACF and PACF functions for the first 50 and 100 observations respectively. Discuss the differences between these plots and the ones you made for part (ii).

The ACF for the first 50 observations declines much faster than the ACF for the first 100 and the ACF for the entire data series. Using the PACF for the first 50 observations, I might only choose 2 lags. Further, the PACF does not decline as fast compared to the ACF as it does looking at the whole series which could provide evidence that I should include an MA term in this specification as well.

#taking the first 50 and 100 observatiosn and plotting their respective acfs and pacfs
first_50_obs <- data$series_two[1:50]

Question 3

Using the variable series_three from the data file, complete the following:

Determine if the variable is stationary. Provide any and all evidence you have to support your answer (e.g.plots, ADF test statistic, etc.).

Series three appears to have somewhat of a trend, although it declines towards the end of the series. The levels of the series are not stationary, visually the data is clearly not mean reverting or homoskedastic. The first differenced data looks stationary based on a visual inspection and the decision heuristic. However, the ADF test is not statistically significant at the 1% level for the first difference, although the ACF for the first difference does appear to decline much faster than the levels data. The data could be trend stationary based on the levels graph indicating a trend but the detrended data does not appear especially mean reverting or homoskedastic.

#plotting series 3
ggplot(data=data) +
  geom_line(aes(x=date, y=series_three), colour="hotpink") +
  ggtitle("Series 3") +
  labs(y = "Series 3", x = "Date")

#additional evidence for difference stationarity 
intord(data$series_three)
